# Workflow

The development cycle, described harness-neutrally. Each phase names what enters it, what it produces, and when to use it. Tools differ per harness; the phases do not.

## The cycle

`brainstorm → plan → execute → review`, with `quick` as the Tier 0–1 shortcut and `debug` as the root-cause entry point. The tier (`risk-tiers.md`) decides how much of the cycle a change runs through: Tier 0 commits directly when there is no behavior change (the branching rules in `commits.md` still apply) and otherwise takes the quick path, Tier 1 takes the quick path with a test, Tier 2+ run the full cycle.

## Brainstorm

Turns an idea into an approved design. Enters: a request or problem. Produces: a written design/spec the implementer can follow, plus explicit approval. Use before any non-trivial new behavior — do not start building until the design is agreed. Prefer a few clarifying questions over guessing the intent. Read the product frame (`PRODUCT.md`) and the decision records (`docs/process/adr/`) relevant to the area first — both are constraints, not open questions: a design that serves no stated goal or violates a non-goal says so and changes the frame in the same effort (or does not proceed); a design that overturns an endorsed decision names the supersession (mandatory rule 4). If the frame is still `not-onboarded`, the start-here onboarding dialogue fills it before product-shaped work.

## Plan

Turns an approved design into a zero-context task breakdown. Enters: the design/spec. Produces: a plan file (`journal-state-plans.md`) of bite-sized, independently testable tasks with exact files, code, and test commands. Assume the implementer knows the toolchain but not this codebase. Use for every Tier 2+ change. The plan names the decision records it read and any new or superseded record the change entails — or states that none apply — and the product goal (`PRODUCT.md`) the change serves, or that it is product-neutral (`journal-state-plans.md`, Plans).

## Execute

Implements the plan task by task. Enters: the plan. Produces: committed, tested code — one atomic commit per task (`commits.md`), following test-driven development (write the failing test, watch it fail, implement, watch it pass, commit). Use as the build phase; keep tasks isolated so each is independently reviewable. A significant, hard-to-reverse decision discovered mid-build stops the task: record it as a decision record first, then write the code that assumes it (mandatory rule 4). Execute runs in the warm production context — the same context that planned the work (`verification-independence.md`).{% if modules.telemetry %} When grading acceptance criteria at checkpoints, append one `GRADE` line per criterion per round to the journal (`docs/process/modules/telemetry.md`).{% endif %}

## Review

The gate before merge to the main branch. Enters: the branch diff plus the plan/spec. Produces: a pass/fail judgment on functional completeness, correctness, and adherence to these rules. The required depth *and independence* scale with the tier (`risk-tiers.md`, `verification-independence.md`): a fresh process reviews a read-only bundle rather than the producing context, and the implementing agent does not self-certify. What a review actually checks — completeness, correctness, security, design, decisions, product frame, tests — is `review-checklist.md`. Use before every merge that the tier gates; fixes loop back through execute + review until clean.{% if modules.telemetry %} Record the per-criterion verdicts as `GRADE` lines with `source=review` in the journal (`docs/process/modules/telemetry.md`).{% endif %}

## Quick

The Tier 0–1 shortcut: no separate plan file. Enters: a small, isolated request. Produces: the change plus a test (Tier 1). State goal, touched files, and risk before editing; escalate to plan if persistence, auth, contracts, or external integrations turn out to be in scope.

## Debug

The root-cause entry point (mandatory rule 6). Enters: a bug, test failure, or unexpected behavior. Produces: a root-cause analysis before any fix. After two failed attempts at a symptom, stop patching and investigate why it happens; fix the cause, not the symptom.
